user_request: A love poem about eyes meeting across a crowded room.
final_poem:
Across the throb of dancers, across
the gauze of cigarette smoke,
your eyes found mine—the way a river
tracks its own course through rock,

unflinching, certain. I had not turned.
The room was filled with other light:
laughter pressed against the walls,
a DJ's fader sliding left to right

like something leaving. Only you
were fixed on me as if I were
the frequency that tuned your equipment.
Only you were pressing in.

And when our gazes locked—I mean
it the way a camera locks—
there was no shutter, no mechanics,
just two apertures wide open

on each other's world. The darkroom
of my chest already developing
your contour at the edge of things I held
beneath the bright bulb, trying to see

what develop means. You didn't smile.
You didn't signal. You stood
in your black jacket, beer whey
around your mouth like something written.

But your eyes—your eyes had already
exposed my interest, developed it
to the grain of I can't look away,
can't look away, and the film

went tight with emotion the way
photographic emulsion does when
it meets the thing it was exposed to.
I didn't know what I was feeling.

You didn't either. We kept dancing.
The floor was tilting now, or so it seemed—
no one else off balance, just us,
the room emptying of everyone

but the image that had already
reversed itself, the negative
standing in for what we started
calling real, calling true,

stuck on the developing tray
between darkness and the bright bulb,
both exposed at once: my heart
split open like a reservoir

letting water back in. Everything
I didn't know I wanted
sat there in your eyes—
the way an emulsion holds

its latent image before
it captures anything, before
the current does its work,
before the print comes off the tray

and you can finally see
what was always already there.
